item.title: EU's Top Court Restricts Personal-Data Transfers to U.S.
item.description: Thousands of companies will face restrictions on storing information about European Union residents on U.S. servers, after the bloc’s top court ruled that such transfers exposed Europeans to American government surveillance without “actionable rights” to challenge it.

item.title: China Is First Major Economy to Return to Growth Since Coronavirus Pandemic
item.description: China’s economy expanded 3.2% in the second quarter from the same period a year earlier, rebounding from a historic coronavirus-induced contraction in the first three months of the year.

item.title: U.S., Gulf Allies Blacklist Islamic State Financial Network
item.description: The U.S. has joined six other nations in sanctioning a financial network linked to the Islamic State terrorist group and its affiliates, blocking any of their assets in the U.S., the Treasury Department said.

item.title: Blaze at Iranian Port Adds to String of Damaging Incidents
item.description: Iranian authorities are investigating a blaze that damaged seven ships in Bushehr port, the latest in a string of fires and explosions that have raised suspicions of sabotage.

item.title: Western Newsrooms Weigh Alternatives to Hong Kong as Beijing Tightens Grip
item.description: For decades, Hong Kong’s press freedoms have made it a hub for Western media organizations covering Asia. Beijing's new national-security law is causing many newsrooms to rethink the city’s status as a haven for journalists.

item.title: Violent Reckoning for Ethiopia's Nobel Laureate Leader
item.description: Targeted killings, deadly street protests, a postponed election and rising regional tensions are destabilizing Ethiopia, posing a stern challenge to the reformist leader of Africa’s second-most populous nation.
